The Church of the Brethren in Nigeria (EYN) has urged President Muhammadu Buhari to deploy more security personnel around Gwoza Hills to guarantee the safe return of internally-displaced persons (IDPs) to their country homes. The president of the church, Rev Joel Billi, made the appeal in Yola, on Thursday, at a press conference in memory of members killed by insurgents. “Deploying a battalion to the volatile areas would help in mitigating further attacks and allow people to go about their farms and other means of livelihood,” Billi emphasised. The cleric stated that the government should, as a matter of urgency, marshal out plans to evacuate the over 47,000 stranded IDPs in Cameroon Camps back to Nigeria. He further called on the North East Development Commission (NEDC) to assist the church by reconstructing houses, schools and worship places destroyed by the terrorists, lamenting that the commission’s impact was yet to be visible in the church. “While we, as a church, supports the federal government’s fight against corruption, we frown at the selective nature of the fight and demand that the rule of law must be respected,” he said. The general secretary of the church, Rev Dr Daniel Mbaya, on his part, lauded government’s efforts towards diversifying the economy, in the midst of COVID-19 challenge. 